1
00:02:33,230 --> 00:02:34,650
What the hell!

2
00:02:35,820 --> 00:02:38,570
Just let us do it tomorrow! Not today!

3
00:02:38,650 --> 00:02:40,860
Hey, I'm just the messenger.

4
00:02:41,530 --> 00:02:44,240
Anyway, the mistress insisted
that it be done today.

5
00:02:44,330 --> 00:02:45,620
That old hag.

6
00:02:46,330 --> 00:02:48,160
All the other times, she leaves us

7
00:02:48,250 --> 00:02:49,910
in charge of guard duty.

8
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,250
Maybe it has something to do with
the reward of three horses.

9
00:02:53,330 --> 00:02:55,710
She wants a part of the reward?

10
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:57,590
What a greedy old hag.

11
00:03:05,810 --> 00:03:06,640
Jeez…

12
00:03:08,930 --> 00:03:10,060
Snake,

13
00:03:10,940 --> 00:03:12,350
will you

14
00:03:12,440 --> 00:03:15,480
let me see my husband, Gardar?

15
00:03:15,570 --> 00:03:16,900
No.

16
00:03:18,990 --> 00:03:21,450
He's injured, isn't he?

17
00:03:22,070 --> 00:03:23,410
How…

18
00:03:23,990 --> 00:03:25,950
How are his wounds?

19
00:03:26,950 --> 00:03:28,790
How would I know?

20
00:03:29,410 --> 00:03:32,920
Why do I have to care for
an enemy who killed my subordinate?

21
00:03:35,500 --> 00:03:37,500
Boss, here's a horse.

22
00:03:37,590 --> 00:03:40,670
All right.
We'll be at the mistress' place.

23
00:03:40,760 --> 00:03:44,260
You go and take Arnheid
back to Gramps' house.

24
00:03:52,390 --> 00:03:55,310
They took the horses
so we don't have any left.

25
00:03:55,980 --> 00:03:58,940
Are you serious? I have to walk…

26
00:03:59,030 --> 00:04:00,490
her back?

27
00:04:07,580 --> 00:04:11,120
Please, let me see my husband.

28
00:04:11,700 --> 00:04:14,750
I swear I'm not thinking of
helping him escape.

29
00:04:14,830 --> 00:04:17,130
I just want to care for his wounds.

30
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:19,920
Huh? Well…

31
00:04:23,260 --> 00:04:26,220
But the boss said…

32
00:04:36,560 --> 00:04:37,610
Hey!

33
00:04:38,310 --> 00:04:40,230
What's going on?

34
00:04:40,820 --> 00:04:43,360
She's the cutie from Master Ketil's place.

35
00:04:44,150 --> 00:04:46,070
Uh, the boss…

36
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:48,200
The boss gave her permission

37
00:04:48,280 --> 00:04:51,200
to care for Gardar's wounds.
I'm not lying!

38
00:05:00,170 --> 00:05:01,550
Gardar…

39
00:05:03,590 --> 00:05:05,010
Arnheid!

40
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:43,170
You were beaten?

41
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:48,890
Please cut this rope, Arnheid.

42
00:05:50,090 --> 00:05:51,800
Let's go home.

43
00:05:52,470 --> 00:05:55,390
-Hey…
-It's fine.

44
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:57,810
She doesn't have any tools
that can cut the rope.

45
00:05:58,390 --> 00:06:00,440
If you say so.

46
00:06:01,110 --> 00:06:02,770
Hey, Arnheid!

47
00:06:02,860 --> 00:06:05,820
Your husband came
all the way here to take you back.

48
00:06:06,400 --> 00:06:10,200
Forget about his wounds. Why don't you
give him something more special?

49
00:06:13,030 --> 00:06:16,080
I can't care for his wounds
if he's tied up like this.

50
00:06:16,620 --> 00:06:18,330
Can you untie him just for now?

51
00:06:18,410 --> 00:06:21,380
That's not going to happen.

52
00:06:21,460 --> 00:06:23,420
His "thing" isn't tied up, though.

53
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:25,590
You can still take care of that.

54
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:28,760
That's right!

55
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:34,220
Arnheid…

56
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:40,900
I'm sorry.

57
00:06:44,980 --> 00:06:46,030
I will

58
00:06:46,610 --> 00:06:48,150
never

59
00:06:48,650 --> 00:06:50,610
leave you and Hjalti

60
00:06:50,700 --> 00:06:52,700
alone again.

61
00:06:53,700 --> 00:06:55,620
Never again…

62
00:06:57,870 --> 00:07:00,830
I was wrong.

63
00:07:02,710 --> 00:07:04,130
Please forgive me,

64
00:07:05,380 --> 00:07:06,920
Arnheid.

65
00:07:35,450 --> 00:07:37,700
I made you suffer so much.

66
00:07:38,450 --> 00:07:40,200
Let's start over.

67
00:07:40,290 --> 00:07:42,670
Let's go back to how it was.

68
00:07:44,330 --> 00:07:46,960
Please let me free.

69
00:07:49,170 --> 00:07:52,050
I'm sorry, Gardar.

70
00:07:52,970 --> 00:07:55,050
I'm sorry.

71
00:08:01,230 --> 00:08:02,850
What are you saying?

72
00:08:02,940 --> 00:08:06,110
I'm the one who must
ask for your forgiveness.

73
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:10,190
Come now, Arnheid.

74
00:08:10,280 --> 00:08:12,150
Get a hold of yourself.

75
00:08:21,660 --> 00:08:23,160
That ruined the mood.

76
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,420
It's starting to rain harder.
I'll take a rest in the hut.

77
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:30,420
What? Hey!

78
00:08:30,510 --> 00:08:32,550
We were told to keep watch.

79
00:08:33,130 --> 00:08:35,260
One person is enough.

80
00:08:35,340 --> 00:08:37,300
You're the one who brought that woman,

81
00:08:37,890 --> 00:08:39,560
so you take responsibility.

82
00:08:40,850 --> 00:08:42,310
Seriously?

83
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:47,770
Hey.

84
00:08:48,860 --> 00:08:51,480
Hey, Arnheid!

85
00:08:51,570 --> 00:08:54,820
Are you done? Isn't that enough?

86
00:09:03,500 --> 00:09:07,460
My only fault
is that I'm a sucker for women.

87
00:09:08,670 --> 00:09:10,460
Your time's up.

88
00:09:12,710 --> 00:09:14,090
Come on, get up.

89
00:10:26,580 --> 00:10:29,620
Arnheid! He has a knife on his belt.

90
00:10:29,710 --> 00:10:31,920
Use that to cut my rope.

91
00:10:33,210 --> 00:10:35,920
Hurry up! Arnheid!

92
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:41,510
Hey! This is bad! He's dead!

93
00:10:41,590 --> 00:10:43,220
I don't know! Just hurry!

94
00:10:43,300 --> 00:10:44,430
Get it together!

95
00:10:45,100 --> 00:10:46,220
Hurry up!

96
00:10:46,720 --> 00:10:48,020
My rope!

97
00:10:49,060 --> 00:10:51,100
We'll both be killed!

98
00:10:56,900 --> 00:10:58,320
Arnheid!

99
00:11:24,140 --> 00:11:25,760
It's no use, Boss.

100
00:11:25,850 --> 00:11:28,100
None of them are breathing.

101
00:11:32,350 --> 00:11:33,980
Those idiots.

102
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:38,070
I told them to not let their guard down
so many times.

103
00:11:42,950 --> 00:11:44,870
Over here, Boss.

104
00:11:47,910 --> 00:11:49,120
His sword…

105
00:11:50,580 --> 00:11:52,500
Take a look at the tip.

106
00:11:53,210 --> 00:11:57,090
The rain washed away the blood,
but there's still oil on it.

107
00:11:57,170 --> 00:11:59,380
He must have stabbed his opponent.

108
00:12:00,460 --> 00:12:02,840
-That's a deep wound.
-Yes.

109
00:12:03,590 --> 00:12:06,220
He was wounded
on top of being wounded already.

110
00:12:07,050 --> 00:12:09,390
There were no horses here either.

111
00:12:11,310 --> 00:12:12,480
Go after him!

112
00:12:13,060 --> 00:12:15,230
He hasn't gone far.

113
00:12:16,110 --> 00:12:18,730
We will settle this on this farm!

114
00:12:20,570 --> 00:12:21,740
As soon as I find him

115
00:12:23,820 --> 00:12:25,570
I will kill him.

116
00:13:00,150 --> 00:13:02,150
You couldn't sleep,

117
00:13:02,230 --> 00:13:03,240
Einar?

118
00:13:07,660 --> 00:13:09,740
You haven't slept yourself.

119
00:13:10,280 --> 00:13:12,450
You weren't woken up by a nightmare.

120
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,290
Yeah…

121
00:13:18,380 --> 00:13:20,170
Were you keeping an eye on me?

122
00:13:21,380 --> 00:13:23,420
Did you think I would

123
00:13:23,510 --> 00:13:25,510
do something crazy during the night?

124
00:13:28,550 --> 00:13:29,800
I wouldn't.

125
00:13:30,390 --> 00:13:32,520
I don't want to make
life harder for Arnheid.

126
00:13:37,810 --> 00:13:39,440
It's not fair, is it?

127
00:13:40,770 --> 00:13:44,240
We were just living in peace, that's all.

128
00:13:46,780 --> 00:13:48,200
Violence

129
00:13:48,860 --> 00:13:51,660
has robbed us of our freedom,
and that's just wrong.

130
00:13:52,740 --> 00:13:54,160
It must be wrong.

131
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:03,340
As someone

132
00:14:04,050 --> 00:14:07,010
who was doing nothing but fighting wars,

133
00:14:07,760 --> 00:14:09,680
I don't have the right to say anything.

134
00:14:10,430 --> 00:14:11,720
But…

135
00:14:12,850 --> 00:14:14,430
it's wrong.

136
00:14:15,270 --> 00:14:16,980
It was wrong.

137
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:21,110
Arnheid

138
00:14:21,190 --> 00:14:23,730
doesn't know that
you used to be a warrior.

139
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:27,860
I'm pathetic.

140
00:14:28,490 --> 00:14:30,110
I'm scared

141
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:33,580
of the thought of people like her
finding that out about me.

142
00:14:35,120 --> 00:14:38,080
How was I able to hurt all those people

143
00:14:38,160 --> 00:14:40,080
like it was nothing?

144
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:44,920
I can't even imagine

145
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:46,170
you being that way.

146
00:14:50,220 --> 00:14:51,640
Hey Thorfinn,

147
00:14:52,470 --> 00:14:54,760
you know that thing you mentioned before?

148
00:14:55,310 --> 00:14:57,770
-Are you serious about it?
-What?

149
00:14:58,850 --> 00:15:00,810
Remember you asked me if I thought

150
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:03,230
it was possible to rid this world

151
00:15:03,310 --> 00:15:04,770
of war and slavery?

152
00:15:06,360 --> 00:15:09,320
It just sounds like a dream to me.

153
00:15:09,860 --> 00:15:12,570
But as someone who has
experienced both sides,

154
00:15:12,660 --> 00:15:14,780
I bet you can come up with an idea.

155
00:15:18,410 --> 00:15:19,660
What do we need to do?

156
00:15:20,790 --> 00:15:21,920
How do we

157
00:15:22,500 --> 00:15:25,170
get rid of war and slavery?

158
00:15:29,800 --> 00:15:31,260
I only know

159
00:15:31,340 --> 00:15:34,050
about the things I experienced myself.

160
00:15:36,260 --> 00:15:39,640
But there's no doubt that wars
produce many slaves.

161
00:15:40,770 --> 00:15:43,150
Those who are defeated in war

162
00:15:43,230 --> 00:15:45,440
are turned into slaves.

163
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:50,070
Just as you and Arnheid were.

164
00:15:51,860 --> 00:15:55,280
The line between warriors
and slave traders is ambiguous.

165
00:15:56,490 --> 00:15:59,700
There are other things
that lead to slavery,

166
00:15:59,790 --> 00:16:02,080
but I think the biggest cause is war.

167
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:06,590
If the number of wars decline
the number of slaves will too.

168
00:16:10,510 --> 00:16:13,340
But Nordic men

169
00:16:13,430 --> 00:16:16,510
don't view war as something bad.

170
00:16:17,930 --> 00:16:21,850
Nordic men measure their worth
by valor and wealth.

171
00:16:22,810 --> 00:16:24,810
The more people you kill

172
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:28,360
and the more wealth you return with,
the more you are respected.

173
00:16:29,730 --> 00:16:32,610
That is why fathers
teach their sons how to fight,

174
00:16:33,360 --> 00:16:36,120
give them weapons and armor,
and take them on warships.

175
00:16:36,780 --> 00:16:39,620
That has always been
the normal thing to do

176
00:16:39,700 --> 00:16:41,790
for us Nordic men.

177
00:16:43,410 --> 00:16:47,710
Whatever it is, it's always difficult
to stop doing what is considered the norm.

178
00:16:50,090 --> 00:16:52,880
But there are also men like you.

179
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:56,470
Is vowing to never hurt another person

180
00:16:56,550 --> 00:16:58,550
such a strange thing to do?

181
00:17:00,720 --> 00:17:02,730
In Nordic society,

182
00:17:03,390 --> 00:17:05,520
cowards cannot survive.

183
00:17:10,440 --> 00:17:11,900
But that's fine.

184
00:17:12,740 --> 00:17:15,570
If it means I don't have to
carry any more of them,

185
00:17:15,650 --> 00:17:18,240
I would happily be an outcast.

186
00:17:20,200 --> 00:17:21,200
"Them"?

187
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:28,670
The dead.

188
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:33,800
The people I have killed.

189
00:17:35,130 --> 00:17:37,800
Their ghosts appear before me
almost every night

190
00:17:38,430 --> 00:17:40,430
and torment me.

191
00:17:41,060 --> 00:17:42,970
They say, "Why did you kill?

192
00:17:43,060 --> 00:17:44,850
After your father was killed,

193
00:17:44,930 --> 00:17:47,940
you were so angry and resentful.

194
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:50,940
So why did you, out of all people,
kill so many

195
00:17:51,020 --> 00:17:53,190
fathers, brothers, and sons?"

196
00:17:55,150 --> 00:17:57,030
I have to make amends

197
00:17:57,110 --> 00:17:59,570
for what I did to these people.

198
00:18:00,120 --> 00:18:02,990
I have to take these people to a place

199
00:18:03,080 --> 00:18:05,120
where they can rest in peace.

200
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:09,540
I'm at my limit.

201
00:18:10,540 --> 00:18:14,170
I can't take on even one more person.

202
00:18:21,180 --> 00:18:22,890
I'm constantly thinking

203
00:18:23,810 --> 00:18:26,810
about how I can repay them.

204
00:18:28,270 --> 00:18:31,940
Vowing to never kill
or destroy anything anymore isn't enough

205
00:18:32,020 --> 00:18:33,770
to be called atonement.

206
00:18:37,030 --> 00:18:40,160
To make up for all the wheat
I've trampled on,

207
00:18:40,240 --> 00:18:42,280
I have to grow more with my own hands.

208
00:18:43,620 --> 00:18:46,330
To make up for
all the houses I've burned down,

209
00:18:46,410 --> 00:18:48,460
I have to build more with my own hands.

210
00:18:49,830 --> 00:18:53,340
I still don't know how to
rid this entire world

211
00:18:53,420 --> 00:18:55,170
of war altogether.

212
00:18:56,170 --> 00:19:00,010
But even if it's just
one place in this world…

213
00:19:00,510 --> 00:19:02,760
It could even be just one village…

214
00:19:05,100 --> 00:19:06,850
I want to create

215
00:19:06,930 --> 00:19:09,560
a place where we no longer need swords.

216
00:19:20,990 --> 00:19:22,490
But

217
00:19:22,570 --> 00:19:25,160
how would you protect that place?

218
00:19:26,660 --> 00:19:28,790
I hate war myself.

219
00:19:29,620 --> 00:19:33,670
But Vikings will come wherever you are.

220
00:19:34,420 --> 00:19:37,050
Sometimes you have to fight

221
00:19:37,130 --> 00:19:39,260
to protect your peace and freedom.

222
00:19:42,970 --> 00:19:43,970
But

223
00:19:45,010 --> 00:19:47,310
that won't do.

224
00:19:48,720 --> 00:19:51,440
There's no point
if you use war to keep peace.

225
00:19:51,940 --> 00:19:53,650
If you do,

226
00:19:53,730 --> 00:19:56,770
you'll never be able to escape
from that bloodstained hell.

227
00:20:02,950 --> 00:20:04,240
I guess

228
00:20:04,990 --> 00:20:07,490
a story that sounds like a dream

229
00:20:07,580 --> 00:20:09,580
is nothing but a dream.

230
00:20:11,660 --> 00:20:14,790
We have to go to the ends of the earth,

231
00:20:14,880 --> 00:20:17,130
somewhere far, far away.

232
00:20:18,050 --> 00:20:21,090
Somewhere even Vikings can't get to.

233
00:20:22,420 --> 00:20:25,260
A land

234
00:20:25,970 --> 00:20:28,220
just for outcasts.

235
00:20:36,610 --> 00:20:39,440
If we run away far beyond the ocean,

236
00:20:39,520 --> 00:20:42,690
I wonder what we'll find there.

237
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:46,450
I'm sure

238
00:20:46,950 --> 00:20:48,450
there will be nothing.

239
00:20:49,330 --> 00:20:52,910
No matter how far you go,
it'll be the same as it is here.

240
00:20:53,710 --> 00:20:57,540
There will only be war and slave traders.

241
00:21:06,970 --> 00:21:08,550
Far west…

242
00:21:09,550 --> 00:21:11,220
Beyond the ocean…

243
00:21:17,810 --> 00:21:20,400
A land out of the reach of any ruler,

244
00:21:20,480 --> 00:21:23,320
a land no slave trader knows about,

245
00:21:23,400 --> 00:21:26,320
a land far beyond the horizon.

246
00:21:29,370 --> 00:21:31,740
There is actually a place like that?

247
00:21:31,830 --> 00:21:35,330
There is. I had forgotten about it.

248
00:21:35,410 --> 00:21:38,170
When I was a child, a sailor named Leif

249
00:21:38,250 --> 00:21:40,250
told me about it.

250
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:43,760
Beyond the vast ocean to the west,

251
00:21:43,840 --> 00:21:46,300
there supposedly is fertile land.

252
00:21:47,010 --> 00:21:49,390
He said there's land that's untouched.

253
00:21:52,140 --> 00:21:54,640
That's amazing.

254
00:21:55,230 --> 00:21:58,400
Then… Then if we go there…

255
00:21:58,480 --> 00:21:59,900
No…

256
00:22:00,860 --> 00:22:03,780
He also told me
that it is tremendously far.

257
00:22:03,860 --> 00:22:05,860
And I don't know the exact location.

258
00:22:08,070 --> 00:22:10,700
Plus, we're talking about
building a nation.

259
00:22:10,780 --> 00:22:13,870
We have to take a multitude
of outcasts there.

260
00:22:14,580 --> 00:22:16,160
It'll be a huge project.

261
00:22:22,750 --> 00:22:24,170
I see.

262
00:22:25,010 --> 00:22:27,050
But you know,

263
00:22:28,720 --> 00:22:32,260
that's the best thing
I've heard in a while.

264
00:23:04,290 --> 00:23:05,500
Be careful.

265
00:23:06,170 --> 00:23:07,340
He's strong.

266
00:23:10,090 --> 00:23:12,720
Wh… What is going on

267
00:23:12,800 --> 00:23:14,510
so early in the morning?

268
00:23:18,980 --> 00:23:22,480
It doesn't seem like anyone's here.

269
00:23:22,560 --> 00:23:25,270
I can't tell with all this junk.

270
00:23:25,360 --> 00:23:28,280
Throw everything out!

271
00:23:31,150 --> 00:23:34,410
Jeez, what is this all about?

272
00:23:36,450 --> 00:23:37,950
He escaped.

273
00:23:38,040 --> 00:23:41,670
-What?
-Gardar escaped.

274
00:23:41,750 --> 00:23:45,460
Is there any other reason
why they would be ransacking our shed?

275
00:23:51,930 --> 00:23:53,510
Arnheid!

276
00:25:53,840 --> 00:25:54,760
''Cause.''

277
00:25:54,840 --> 00:25:56,010
Subtitle translation by: Kiko Morita

